007506fccdd19445fda861163670f1f9.text: I have again reverted drastic edits to this article, which were implemented without community consensus. I encourage editors to review [[WP:CONSENSUS]] and [[WP:BRD]] to learn about the editing process here on Wikipedia if they are not familiar with them. If editors continue to try to force content into this high-visibility and long-standing article, it may be necessary to request intervention of an uninvolved administrator. However, allow me to explain further my objection to the drastic change and the need I see for a community discussion.

2f754978297906f7d9360c413f896c9a.text: I agree there is a need to improve the article's coverage of the university's environmental impact. However, the proposed changes (see [http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Cornell_University&diff=551801685&oldid=551729625 diff]) introduced several other problems:

6ad2b4d712298823db8dc5f9418aeed2.text: #The information belongs under the Campuses:Ithaca section, not under Academics, since it only really covers impact of the Ithaca campus -- if content about other campuses were mentioned, it would probably best fall under the appropriate campus subsection, but definitely not under Academics, unless the information has to do with Cornell curricula on environmental issues

d8231591aa569e580ce49d9e68024be1.text: #The proposed text violated [[WP:OR]] by presenting a [[WP:SYNTHESIS|synthesis]] of research about fracking in order to advance a certain viewpoint

635c4f63ab94de7114184d7c7364d449.text: #The proposed text presented unverified information (e.g., Black Oak Wind Farm) and had an inoperable link to a Forbes article by Skorton

1f8eb61ae7cb2dd41afbc6de7e1f5252.text: #The proposed text was unnecessarily wordy and broke out small paragraphs into several subsections, when Wikipedia strives for succinctness

318456a7b4f27e4131cfc6b5f3f004ad.text: #The proposed text referenced a decline in Cornell's performance in the STARS review, a statement which again had no explicit backing from reliable sources

a801146fc89b493dac6c5196bcf5fcfe.text: #The proposed text mentions an unnotable vote on fossil fuels (covered in Cornell Daily Sun) and then an irrelevant mention of efforts at Yale, which is also not supported by [[WP:RS|reliable sources]]

ae4a8523831656171da0ae90599307ea.text: The current coverage of environmental issues in this article is not perfect, but the proposed changes only seemed to make issues worse (à la [[WP:UNDUE]]). I would encourage interested editors to build upon the current text -- not wholly replace it -- and to propose notable strings of information one-by-one here for the community's approval. Several editors are active on this page and happy to collaborate. Cheers. —'''''[[User:Eustress|Eustress]]''''' <sup>''[[User talk:Eustress|talk]]''</sup> 15:15, 23 April 2013 (UTC)

She said she could work on it tomorrow. If I can ask a favor, would you mind taking a look at the [http://climatechallenge.org/wiki-task-force/toolkit toolkit we have here] and let us know if there are ways we can improve it so that students who want to engage with this community can do so as constructively as possible? 38f1dfab20d7488e134c1ac5b73c2b98.text: Cornell has an endowment of over $5 billion.<ref>{{cite web|last=Doolittle|first=Nancy|title=Endowment return positive in FY2012|url=http://www.news.cornell.edu/stories/Nov12/Endowment.html|publisher=Ezra Magazine}}</ref>  The University does not disclose the details of its investments however it is known that it invests a significant portion of its endowment in the energy sector, thus profitting from coal, oil, and shale-gas extraction. Cornell received a 0.41 / 9.00 on the STARS review for Positive Sustainability Investments, a decline from previous years<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stars.aashe.org/institutions/cornell-university-ny/report/2013-03-08/12/56/404/}}</ref> .

49e1966cd643617bab3f63f63c49676d.text: == Does John Cleese truly represent "Famous current and former Cornell faculty"? ==

828f1ce9f4e9d2ba96728e7a8544c8b7.text: Cleese has been represented in the article as "Famous current and former Cornell faculty" for quite a long time, and I think it's misleading. I wonder if anyone else feels the same. Cleese's appointment is "Professor at Large," and later "Provost’s Visiting Professor." As I understand it, he doesn't teach any class on the schedule that you could actually take. He shows up once a year to give a public lecture and maybe visits a class of his choosing. According to [https://news.cornell.edu/stories/2018/10/new-book-john-cleese-his-element-cornell this article] he visited seven times between 1999-2007. He has none of the responsibilities of an actual faculty member, in the sense of publishing, teaching, advising, etc. However, I'm not on campus. Does it really feel to the students like Cleese is part of Cornell? - [[User:Kzirkel|Kzirkel]] ([[User talk:Kzirkel|talk]]) 15:23, 29 June 2019 (UTC)
